Whenever Spring manages a bean, it takes care of creating it, injecting dependencies, initializing it, and finally destroying it when the container shuts down.
 
A Spring bean generally goes through these phases:
Instantiation → Object of bean class is created.
Dependency Injection → Spring injects required dependencies (via constructor/setter).
Initialization (post-construct phase) → After dependencies are set, Spring allows us to run custom initialization logic (this is like post construct).
Ready for Use → Bean can now be used by the application.
Destruction (Pre-Destroy phase) → Before container shuts down, Spring calls custom cleanup logic (this is like pre destroy).

@PostConstruct (Post-Construct phase)
•@PostConstruct Called automatically after dependency injection is completed.
• @PostConstructUsed to perform initialization tasks like setting up resources or validating data.
• @PostConstruct Executed once after the bean is created.
•@PostConstruct Equivalent to the init-method phase.

@PreDestroy (Pre-Destroy phase)
•@PreDestroy  Called just before the bean is destroyed by the container.
•@PreDestroy  Used to release resources, close connections, or perform cleanup.
•@PreDestroy  Executed once before the bean is removed.
•@PreDestroy  Equivalent to the destroy-method phase.

🔹 Additional Note
• To use @PostConstruct and @PreDestroy, you need to add the Annotation API dependency from the Maven repository in your project.

Old:
import javax.annotation.PostConstruct;

New (Spring Boot 3+):
import jakarta.annotation.PostConstruct;

You don’t usually need to manually add dependency in modern Spring Boot — it’s already included.

2. Scope Matters
For singleton beans → @PreDestroy is called 
For prototype beans → @PreDestroy is NOT called automatically 
3. Order of Execution

Initialization order:

Constructor → Dependency Injection → @PostConstruct

Destruction order:

@PreDestroy → Bean destroyed

